in the happiness of pursuit for the pursuit of happiness wherein lies the happiness the way you have worded your question is logically challenging it doesn't really ask about the pursuit of happiness it asks about pursuing the pursuit of happiness which means that for some reason a person is not actually able or willing to look for happiness but is happy just to be trying to find the time or opportunity to pursue happiness and if that is the case a paradox arises because the person already has happiness as long as they believe the time or opportunity to look for it will come yet they already have what they seek so the answer to the question is the first part of the question itself Goodness and value theory Nicomachean Ethics Meaning of life Philosophy of language Theory of conduct Peter Singer Paradox Lie Human Fallacy Objectivist philosophy Immanuel Kant Logic Legacy of Kain Zeno's paradoxes Opus Dei Past teachings of Prem Rawat Happiness Epistemology Current teachings of Prem Rawat Quizbowl Intelligent design Moral Politics Grelling-Nelson paradox A Course In Miracles Scientology beliefs and practices Aristotle Infant baptism Microeconomics Predestination G__del's incompleteness theorem Republic (dialogue) Esperanto grammar Expert system Theodicy Liberalism Monty Hall problem Donald Davidson (philosopher) Capitalism Philosophy of mathematics Karl Popper Appeal Identity and change Pascal's Wager Empiricism Fahrenheit 451 Phaedo Willard Van Orman Quine Western philosophy English grammar Ludwig Wittgenstein 2005 trial of Michael Jackson Natural law Philosophical skepticism Modal logic Newcomb's paradox African philosophy Deconstruction Vacuous truth Paradox of hedonism Religion Creationism David Hume Eutheism, dystheism, and maltheism Hedonism Family Feud Consensus decision-making Avenue Q Falsifiability Leviathan (book) Noam Chomsky Translation Sant Thakar Singh The Hitchhiker's Guide to the Galaxy (film) Tax protester Soul The nature of God in Western theology Altr